  <h1>Introduction to C++</h1>
  
  <div class="overview">
    <p>
      C++ is a powerful, general-purpose programming language that was developed by Bjarne Stroustrup 
      at Bell Labs starting in 1979. It's an extension of the C programming language, which is why 
      it was initially called "C with Classes."
    </p>
    
    <p>
      C++ combines the efficiency and flexibility of C with object-oriented programming features, 
      making it suitable for a wide range of applications from system software to games, 
      embedded systems, and high-performance applications.
    </p>
  </div>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Why Learn C++?</h2>
    
    <div class="benefits-grid">
      <div class="benefit">
        <h3>üöÄ Performance</h3>
        <p>C++ provides low-level control and high performance, making it ideal for system programming and applications where speed matters.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="benefit">
        <h3>üèóÔ∏è Versatility</h3>
        <p>From operating systems to game engines, from embedded systems to web servers, C++ is used everywhere.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="benefit">
        <h3>üìö Foundation</h3>
        <p>Learning C++ provides a strong foundation for understanding computer science concepts and other programming languages.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="benefit">
        <h3>üíº Career Opportunities</h3>
        <p>C++ skills are highly valued in the software industry, especially for system-level programming and performance-critical applications.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Basic Structure of a C++ Program</h2>
    
    <p>Every C++ program has a specific structure. Let's examine the components of a simple program:</p>

    <CodeExample 
      client:load
      title="Basic C++ Program Structure"
      code={`// Include header files
#include <iostream>

// Use standard namespace
using namespace std;

// Main function - entry point of the program
int main() {
    // Program statements
    cout << "Welcome to C++ Programming!" << endl;
    
    // Return statement
    return 0;
}`}
      explanation="This shows the basic structure: include directives, namespace declaration, main function, and return statement. Every C++ program must have a main() function which serves as the entry point."
      output="Welcome to C++ Programming!"
    />

    <h3>Component Breakdown:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>#include &lt;iostream&gt;</strong> - Includes the input/output stream library</li>
      <li><strong>using namespace std;</strong> - Allows us to use standard library functions without std:: prefix</li>
      <li><strong>int main()</strong> - The main function where program execution begins</li>
      <li><strong>cout</strong> - Standard output stream for displaying text</li>
      <li><strong>endl</strong> - Inserts a newline and flushes the output buffer</li>
      <li><strong>return 0;</strong> - Indicates successful program termination</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Comments in C++</h2>
    
    <p>Comments are essential for code documentation and readability. C++ supports two types of comments:</p>

    <CodeExample 
      client:load
      title="Single-line and Multi-line Comments"
      code={`#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    // This is a single-line comment
    cout << "Hello, World!" << endl;
    
    /*
       This is a multi-line comment
       It can span multiple lines
       Useful for longer explanations
    */
    
    cout << "Comments help make code readable!" << endl;
    
    return 0; // Another single-line comment
}`}
      explanation="Single-line comments start with // and continue to the end of the line. Multi-line comments are enclosed between /* and */ and can span multiple lines."
      output={`Hello, World!
Comments help make code readable!`}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Basic Input and Output</h2>
    
    <p>C++ uses streams for input and output operations. The most commonly used are <code>cout</code> for output and <code>cin</code> for input:</p>

    <CodeExample 
      client:load
      title="Input and Output Operations"
      code={`#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    string name;
    int age;
    
    // Output - asking for input
    cout << "Enter your name: ";
    cin >> name;
    
    cout << "Enter your age: ";
    cin >> age;
    
    // Output - displaying results
    cout << "Hello, " << name << "!" << endl;
    cout << "You are " << age << " years old." << endl;
    
    return 0;
}`}
      explanation="This example demonstrates basic input/output. 'cin' reads input from the user, and 'cout' displays output. The >> operator extracts data from the input stream, while << inserts data into the output stream."
      output={`Enter your name: Alice
Enter your age: 25
Hello, Alice!
You are 25 years old.`}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Compilation Process</h2>
    
    <p>Understanding how C++ code becomes an executable program is important:</p>
    
    <div class="compilation-steps">
      <div class="step">
        <h4>1. Preprocessing</h4>
        <p>The preprocessor handles directives like #include and #define, expanding them into the source code.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="step">
        <h4>2. Compilation</h4>
        <p>The compiler translates the preprocessed source code into assembly language or object code.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div class="step">
        <h4>3. Linking</h4>
        <p>The linker combines object files and libraries to create the final executable program.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="terminal-example">
      <h4>Common Compilation Commands:</h4>
      <pre><code># Compile and run a C++ program
g++ -o program program.cpp
./program

# Compile with debugging information
g++ -g -o program program.cpp

# Compile with optimization
g++ -O2 -o program program.cpp</code></pre>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Practice Exercise</h2>
    
    <div class="exercise">
      <h3>Exercise 1: Your First Program</h3>
      <p>Write a C++ program that:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Asks the user for their favorite programming language</li>
        <li>Asks for how many years they've been programming</li>
        <li>Displays a personalized message with this information</li>
      </ol>
      
      <details>
        <summary>Solution</summary>
        <CodeExample 
          client:load
          title="Exercise Solution"
          code={`#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    string language;
    int years;
    
    cout << "What's your favorite programming language? ";
    cin >> language;
    
    cout << "How many years have you been programming? ";
    cin >> years;
    
    cout << "\\nGreat! You've been programming in " << language;
    cout << " for " << years << " years!" << endl;
    cout << "Welcome to the world of C++!" << endl;
    
    return 0;
}`}
          explanation="This solution uses string and int variables to store user input, then displays a formatted message using the input values."
        />
      </details>
    </div>
  </section>

